name.text: Simplification of rational expressions in partial fractions: 1.8 a,c

questiontext.text:
Write the rational expression below as a sum of its partial fractions.

\(\qquad \displaystyle {@question_expression2@}=\) [[input:ans3]] \(+\) [[input:ans4]] \(+\) [[input:ans5]]

\(\hspace{6cm} \) [[validation:ans3]]\(\hspace{1.5cm} \) [[validation:ans4]] \(\hspace{1.5cm} \) [[validation:ans5]]

\(\quad \) [[feedback:prt2]]

generalfeedback.text:
To write \( \displaystyle {@question_expression2@}\) as a sum of its partial fractions we need to follow the steps below:

\[{@question_expression2@} ={@part_frac_Aa@}+{@part_frac_Bb@}+{@part_frac_Cc@}\]

Setting the numerators equal gives:

\[{@expra@}\]

Getting the coefficients \(A\) and \(B\), we have

Let \(x=0:\quad {@expr1a@} \implies {@expAa@}\).

Let \(x={@-const_3@}:\quad {@expr2b@} \implies {@expCc@}\).

Let \(x={@(-const_2/const_1)@}:\quad {@expr3bc@} \implies {@expBb@}\).

The partial fraction is then,

\[{@expr3c@}\]
